title: For Trade:  Japanese Type 26 (1893) revolver
postcontent:
"Japanese Type 26 (1893) revolver, some of which were still in use during WWII. That one may have been captured, but more likely was taken from a depot in Japan at the end of the war. The engraving is typical Japanese, so it is reasonable to suppose that either the first American owner or a subsequent one was stationed in Japan and had the engraving done there. After the war, the Japanese economy was in bad shape and Japanese engravers did such work at modest cost. In fact, that kind of engraving was often called "carton of cigarettes" engraving because that was the usual cost. Perhaps the grip work earned the Japanese workman another carton!

It is hard to tell the quality of the engraving, but it doesn't look bad. I suspect those grips may be real ivory. I think that grip could be repaired, but I would want to consult an expert in that area. My WAG is that the gun could easily bring $1000 or more, but I would defer to anyone who may be more expert in that area."

title: For Sale/Trade:  308 nato headspace gauge
postcontent:
for sale or trade--make me an offer. this is a NATO headspace gauge for 
checking military rifle chambers for safety. you simply insert this into the 
chamber and release the bolt. if it closes, the gun is unsafe to fire. it is called a field gauge. important to have when purchasing rifles with military chambers. NATO headspace is different for 7.62x51 than winchester 308. a military rifle may close on a 308 headspace gauge indicating dangerous condition, but still be perfectly safe to fire. also a good way to not be ripped off by someone using a 308 win gauge to tell you your military rifle such as the norinco/polytech m14 is unsafe to sell.
